Pillar 3 - Biodiversity

Via a partnership with UNESCO, LVMH is committed to safeguarding nature.

As the world leader in luxury, LVMH has been committed to making the protection of biodiversity an absolute priority. When it comes to building a more sustainable future, the Group pledges to be an audacious, creative and exemplary actor. The protection of nature’s ecosystems has always been of utmost importance to LVMH, whose activity is significantly reliant on natural raw materials (flowers, grapes, cotton, leather, stones etc.). Therefore, LVMH is taking action and making the protection and regeneration of biodiversity a key pillar of its LIFE 360 environmental strategy.

 

 

In 2019 LVMH strengthened its commitment to protecting the environment with the signature of a five-year partnership with UNESCO to support the Man and Biosphere (MAB) program. 

 

UNESCO, MAB & LIFE 360

LVMH’s five-year partnership with UNESCO, signed in 2019, is designed to support the Man and Biosphere (MAB) program, an intergovernmental scientific program that aims to establish a scientific basis for enhancing the relationship between people and their environments.

 

This partnership makes a decisive contribution to advancing concrete initiatives by LVMH and its Maisons. In March 2021, LVMH revealed its new biodiversity strategy. It is one of the pillars of the new LIFE 360 program, and aims to have a positive net contribution to biodiversity.

 

The LVMH Group's Biodiversity Strategy

Our biodiversity strategy has been structured around four objectives:

 

1. Establishing a clear and precise measurement of biodiversity impact: Measurement is a potent tool for defining priorities, objectives and actions. LVMH works on the deployment of measurement tools such as the Global Biodiversity Score, and uses life-cycle analysis with geo-located biodiversity indicators that are continuously enriched through collaborations with scientific experts in this field.

 

2. Avoiding and reducing impact on ecosystems: The Group is committed to not using raw materials from zones with a high risk of deforestation or desertification. In addition, by 2026, LVMH will roll out certification systems corresponding to the most rigorous standards of biodiversity-related criteria, and apply them across its strategic supply network.

 

3. Promoting animal welfare: Following the implementation of its Charter on animal welfare in the procurement of raw materials, the Group has set a deadline of 2026 for the full deployment of the standards and good practices defined.

 

4. Regenerating ecosystems by 2030: The Group has announced the deployment of regenerative agriculture programs, for strategic agricultural raw materials such as grapes, cotton, wool and leather. It has also promised to contribute to the collective effort of regenerating ecosystems and preserving endangered plant and animal species. The objective is to regenerate the equivalent of 5 million hectares of habitat for flora and fauna – and all of the above by 2030.

 

Some of our Preservation Programs

A number of ambitious preservation programs launched within the Group include:

  • The “Guerlain for Bees Conservation” program, which includes “Women for Bees”
  • The Moët Hennessy “Living Soils” program for soil regeneration
  • The regenerative-agriculture pilot projects launched with the backing of Stella McCartney.

 

Within this framework, LVMH and UNESCO have launched a program to target the factors of deforestation in the Amazon.
